node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.text:
In search of a quiet getaway that could double as a holiday hub for extended family and friends, a Mexico City couple found a three-and-a-half-acre property in Valle de Bravo, a popular weekend destination two hours from the capital. The couple reached out to architects @javiersanchezcorral and @carloscmar who collaborated on a plan for three “floating monoliths” that rise from the landscape. Inspired by Donald Judd’s minimalist works, the three volumes feature board-formed concrete walls with charred wood accents and strategically placed cutouts to frame views of the surrounding terrain. “Weekend estates should push users to experience life differently from the way they do in the city,” says Sánchez. “Splitting the residence into smaller ‘houses’ creates independence for multiple inhabitants, while walking from one volume to the next allows for contemplation and engagement with the landscape, the weather, and the views.” Tour the commanding, concrete trio when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.
–
Photos by @rafaelgamo

A dusty-pink facade is only a hint of what’s inside this 18th-century structure. For Sérgio Antunes, cofounder of Lisbon-based @auroraarquitectos, the charming exterior and its rich pigment provided a fascinating starting point for the renovation of the Rose Building—a single-family residence in southern Portugal that he and @furo_architecturestudio turned into five glowing apartments. Throughout are huge swaths of color with unique touches: For example, painted on the ceiling of the central stair is a moody mural of a woman in the style of a fresco, and in one of the unit’s bathrooms, more artwork on the ceiling depicts a mermaid emerging from a swirl of waves. Elsewhere, arched windows, sloped ceilings, ornate moldings, and wooden doors elegantly play off Portuguese marble and patterned ceramic tiles. With the go-ahead from the city, the architects were also able to construct a modern addition at the rear—The Mustard Building—that pairs natural wood partitions with the subdued tones of creamy terrazzo. For more of the dazzling residence-turned-apartment building, head to the link in bio.

After acquiring enough screen time to last a lifetime, tech industry couple Mike Romanowicz and Lizzie Kardon were craving a change of pace. So, the husband and wife headed to the Catskills, fell in love with an 8-acre wooded plot of land, and set out to build a small cabin. “This was an arbitrary challenge for ourselves,” Romanowicz said. “Could we get out of our comfort zone and build something physical?” In testing their limits, they not only designed and constructed their own minimalist getaway, but also came up with a business plan, too. “Having done that project, and given our background, we figured we could make this experience easier for people to follow in our footsteps,” Romanowicz said. @denoutdoors, a do-it-yourself-cabin-company they launched in July of 2020, provides people with a catalog of building plans that include A-frame and barn house designs. With their own 834-square-foot cabin as an example, they’re promoting a “less is more” philosophy—a concept they hope to pass on to those interested in building their own minimalist retreats. Tour the couple’s Catskills cabin, known as Fox Den, at the link in bio.

Walls are out. Curtains are up. Acclaimed for their nifty storage tactics and clever spatial arrangements, the architects at @burr.studio have again surpassed small-space expectations. “This time around, we transformed a humble apartment built in the ‘70s into an experimental dwelling,” says the Madrid-based firm. "The independent rooms were strictly compiled, reducing each one’s potential size and function," the architects continue. "Our proposed transformation radically opposed this layout, as we sought to dismantle the divisions between spaces and dissolve the limits of each." Through the use of a central core that integrates the main facilities—note that the toilet can be isolated—tenants are able to build, or break down, spaces as they choose, from a study space to a private bedroom. The curtains themselves are also notable, created from spatially-relevant materials that nod to their function, like a quilted cloth for the bedroom, or a noise-reducing series of felt strips for a home office. In total, these space-saving solutions allow the small-yet-fully-equipped dwelling to effectively serve multiple purposes, all while accommodating modern living. Take a peek behind the curtain at the link in bio.

“This is the cheapest house either of our offices have ever worked on,” say homeowners and architects Ernesto Crangolino and Krista Whitson of @alterstudio and @ml_arch, respectively. At a final construction cost of $550,000—landscaping and a solar array pushed it slightly over budget, but made the home net zero—the couple achieved this svelte four-bedroom in Austin, Texas, that was largely designed out of the circumstances of a constrained lot. “We hate it when architecture is a consequence of forces outside of it,” say the architects, “but it meant that the house had to be very agile and responsive.” Check out the cleverly compact home, included in last year’s @aiaaustin Home Tours, at the link in our bio.

Many can attest to the fact that siblings challenge us in the best ways. This time, architect @pollyharbisondesign, who usually gravitates toward a relaxed minimalism, was tasked by her sister, Margot, with a renovation that embraces color and texture. Luckily, the 1940s home, located in the Sydney suburb of Lindfield, came with inspiration a few steps outside. “Ewen loves these eclectic, crazy, colorful flowers,” Margot says about her husband and the garden that runs parallel to their home. With the help of @arentpykestudio—who added rich textures and finishes, such as the marble that runs from countertop to stairway to checkered floor—Polly was able to strike a balance between old and new. The old home, with only the loss of a small area that’s been repurposed as a brick courtyard, stands nearly untouched next to its accompanying addition that houses a kitchen, living room, primary bedroom, and bathroom that leads directly to an outdoor shower overlooking the greenery. "Despite all this clash of materials and color, the overriding sense of the building is that it’s very calm," Polly says. "It’s got almost a monastic calm feeling to it and it’s all about this lovely green garden." Take a look at the striking, yet serene home at the link in bio.

When Joe and Ali Pivar purchased their 1890s townhouse in Red Hook in late 2012, the house, unaltered since the ’70s, was a warren of dark rooms. A gut job was needed, which Joe largely took on himself. By the time the couple met their architect, Allison Reeves of @ardesign.nyc, through friends, the house had been hollowed to a shell. “Before construction, we removed every finish and covering to expose the layers beneath. It was almost like an archaeological exercise,” says the architect. In her design, Reeves “flipped” the layout of the two floors the couple use—totaling 1,200 square feet—putting the kitchen and living area on the top level and the bedrooms on the level below. The simplified interior allowed Reeves to focus on the one feature the owners wanted most: light. She removed the old pitched roof, and, by installing heavy-duty reclaimed timber beams, was able to raise the ceiling to almost 12 feet in the front half of the house. The heightened volume provides space for a large glass bulkhead above the stairs. Additional light now funnels in through an oversized, angled box window that takes the place of two existing windows in the new dark gray brick facade. Read the full feature at the link in bio.

When Daniel Rabin and @annie.ritz of local architecture and design firm @andandandstudio were brought on to renovate a home in Los Angeles’s Atwater Village, they discovered it had been built as part of a wartime effort wherein women were enlisted to construct housing out of prefabricated wall panels. “Very cool history,” says Rabin, “but we had walls built out of two-by-two-foot lumber and brick foundations.” That was just the start. “It was in terrible shape: dark, dank, rotten, and a series of ad hoc additions over time made for a cramped and confusing layout,” says Rabin. Discovering that much of the house was not salvageable, the duo set to work crafting a new home on the existing footprint. The new 1,500-square-foot home features three bedrooms and two bathrooms, along with a combined kitchen, dining, and living area that spills out onto an exterior deck. All in, the design draws on the original home’s storied past while writing a new future for the owners. “They are a young family and this is their first home, so they came to the table with many goals and aspirations,” says Rabin. “They wanted to capture the quintessential California style of living, with areas flowing from inside to outside, and lots of bright, sunny spaces to move through.” Tour the reimagined Atwater Village bungalow, known as the Pink House, at the link in bio.

On the outskirts of Madrid, architect Malu de Miguel jumped at the opportunity to work with her ideal clients: her own kin. "My family had the plot for around 25 years," she explains. “A couple of years ago, my dad retired, and because the house we lived in had a lot of stairs, my parents decided to build a new one.” The move to create something new was the perfect chance for the family to find common, shared ground. Now, @malu_de_miguel lives in the residence year-round with her husband and their two small children, while her parents split their time between Gran Canaria and Madrid. Malu’s two brothers—located in Mexico and Japan—are able to share the space as well. The roughly 3,390-square-foot house is split into two separate pavilions connected by an enclosed patio. The main pavilion, where Malu and family live, has three bedrooms, while the smaller pavilion has two, an ideal setup to accommodate frequent visitors. Designing a multigenerational home isn’t just about bed count, though: Malu sought balance by pairing softer, rustic materials with cool concrete and glass, reflecting the tastes of her family members. Now, the two units share space seamlessly, while also maintaining access to private terraces and internal courtyards throughout. Though they close street-facing windows at night, the family enjoys communal space by leaving open all interior partitions. “We open up the enclosed patio in March, and we close it in October," she jokes. Take a full tour of the Spanish home at the link in bio.

From the outside, this New England cottage blends demurely into the landscape, with its quiet, artfully weathered cedar shingles and moss-green door. But on the inside, a floor-to-ceiling, white-on-white palette gives the home an attention-grabbing glow—it’s truly a work of art, inside and out. What was once a DHL delivery van is now the mobile home for a pair of adventurous climbers, @charlielow and @dalemcomley. Though the British couple had recently tackled their own home renovation, there was still a long road ahead—and a lot to learn—on the journey to Ringo, their flipped 2013 sprinter. “We didn’t have any previous experience with a lot of this, so we started from scratch by watching videos and reading blogs," they say. "We learned so much! Everything from plumbing to electrical to gas.” After purchasing the van for $11,377, the couple got to planning, aiming for an $8,500 project budget. “You need to ensure you know where you will want lights so you can run cable to the correct places—once you’ve installed all of the cladding, it’s so much harder to go back and do this,” says a pragmatic Charlie. With solar power, new windows, and interiors on par with many stationary dwellings, the results speak for themselves. See the complete budget breakdown behind @climbingvan when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.
